<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-08-25T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-08-25T12:00:00-05:00" n="611" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d611">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.162/27: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Salvador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Engert</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">San
                                        Salvador</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-08-25T11:00:00-06:00"><hi rend="italic">August 25,
                                        1925—11 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 6:48
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>61. Draft of the treaty of friendship, commerce and consular rights was
                            submitted to the Foreign Office this morning.</p>
                        <p>I should appreciate it if the Department could for my confidential
                            guidance telegraph briefly principal grounds on which
                            most-favored-nation <pb facs="1029" n="933" xml:id="pg_933"/> treatment
                            is desired to be used discreetly in conversation without committing the
                            Department in any way.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>